# dotw-terraform

## Canonical Repository URL

<https://github.com/tmilkotev/dotw-terraform>

## Purpose

A structured, multi-account AWS lab environment built with Terraform, designed to develop practical, production-aligned cloud and infrastructure-as-code skills.

Primary goals:

- Provide a meaningful, hands-on AWS learning environment
- Model real-world multi-account architecture
- Enable safe experimentation under strict cost constraints
- Serve as the cloud infrastructure layer within the DOTW ecosystem

## Scope and Boundaries

In Scope:

- AWS multi-account foundational architecture
- Core infrastructure provisioning via Terraform
- Networking (VPC, subnets, routing)
- Compute (EC2, Lambda)
- Storage (S3, DynamoDB)
- Databases (RDS – controlled usage)
- IAM and security constructs
- Basic monitoring and logging (CloudWatch)
- Budgeting and cost alerting

Out of Scope:

- Kubernetes or container platform deployment
- Application deployment workflows
- CI/CD systems
- Advanced observability stacks (Prometheus, Grafana, Loki)
- Platform orchestration (handled by dotw-platformctl)
- High-cost AWS services (e.g., NAT Gateway, EKS, ALB)

## Architecture Overview

The system is based on a production-inspired multi-account AWS structure.

Accounts:

- management  
- network  
- workload  
- security  

Responsibilities:

- management: global configuration, budgets, future shared services
- network: VPC and networking primitives
- workload: compute, storage, and lab workloads
- security: IAM, audit, and security-related services

The architecture follows a foundation-first approach:

- Establish account structure
- Build networking baseline
- Add compute and storage layers
- Introduce monitoring and cost controls

Accounts are initially isolated, with connectivity introduced later if required.

