## Core Concepts

- Multi-account architecture as a first-class design principle
- Infrastructure as Code using Terraform only (no orchestration layer)
- Foundation-first progression before adding higher-level services
- Strict cost-awareness and resource lifecycle control
- Modular Terraform design for reuse and clarity
- Production-inspired patterns adapted for lab scale

## Design Decisions

- Terraform is executed standalone and not via platformctl
- Multi-account structure includes management, network, workload, and security accounts
- State is initially stored locally to avoid external dependencies
- Architecture prioritizes realism while remaining within free-tier constraints
- Services are selected based on relevance to SRE roles and real-world usage
- High-cost managed services are intentionally excluded from early stages

## Constraints

Cost constraints:

- Must remain within AWS free tier whenever possible
- No always-on paid resources
- No NAT Gateway, load balancers, or paid control planes
- EC2 instances must be stoppable and minimal size (t2.micro/t3.micro)
- RDS usage must be minimal, controlled, or optional
- Storage usage must remain small and monitored

Service constraints:

- Prefer free or low-cost services
- Avoid high-throughput or high-frequency workloads
- Avoid multi-AZ and high-availability configurations initially

State constraints:

- Terraform state stored locally in early phases
- Remote state (S3 + DynamoDB) deferred to later stage

## AWS Service Classification

FREE:

- IAM
- VPC
- Security Groups
- NACLs
- Route Tables
- CloudWatch (basic metrics)
- CloudTrail (basic)
- AWS Budgets
- Auto Scaling (control plane)

SEMI-FREE:

- EC2 (free tier limited)
- S3 (limited storage and requests)
- DynamoDB (limited capacity)
- Lambda (limited invocations)
- CloudWatch Logs (limited ingestion)

SEMI-PAID:

- RDS (free tier with constraints)
- EBS volumes
- Route 53

PAID (avoid initially):

- NAT Gateway
- Application/Network Load Balancers
- EKS
- OpenSearch
- ElastiCache
- VPC endpoints (certain types)

## Operational Model

- Terraform is executed per account or per component
- Infrastructure is built incrementally from foundation to services
- Resources are created, tested, and destroyed as part of learning cycles
- Cost monitoring is implemented early via budgets and alerts
- Future enhancements may include automated shutdown of idle resources

## Quality Bar

- Deterministic and reproducible Terraform deployments
- Clear separation between accounts and responsibilities
- Strict adherence to cost constraints
- Minimal but realistic architecture aligned with industry practices
- Clean, modular Terraform code structure
- Alignment with real-world SRE expectations

